crops.presented_by: Dr. J. Dufrenoy
crops.institution_involved: Station de Pathologie Vegetale, Pont de la Maye, Gironde
crops.description: Seeds presented by Dr. J. Dufrenoy, Station de Pathologie Vegetale, Pont de la Maye, Gironde. A hardy perennial grown in the Pyrenees; noted in the record as originally from Liberia.

crops.presented_by: Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum
crops.institution_involved: Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum (Soledad, Cienfuegos)
crops.description: Seeds presented by Robert M. Grey, Superintendent, Atkins Institution of the Arnold Arboretum, Soledad, Cienfuegos. An erect shrub or small tree with obtusely lobed leathery leaves broader than long and few-flowered clusters of pure yellow flowers. Noted as native to India. Reference to previous introduction: see 98802.

crops.presented_by: McGregor Museum, Kimberley
crops.institution_involved: McGregor Museum, Kimberley
crops.description: Seeds presented by the McGregor Museum, Kimberley. A strongly resin-scented shrub native to southern Africa, with oblong to obovate entire leaves up to 2 inches long and short racemes of small woolly flower heads. Reported to be good stock feed and drought resistant. Reference to previous introduction: see 98012.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. Described as a South African bulbous plant with six to nine linear-subulate, channeled, hairy leaves about a foot long and green, yellow-margined flowers in a lax raceme borne on a scape as long as the leaves.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. A handsome tropical tree native to Malaya, with ovate-oblong acute leaves and very numerous pale-rose flowers in much-branched terminal panicles; noted as larger in all parts than Lagerstroemia indica.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. A tall tropical tree 70 to 100 feet high with elliptic-lanceolate leaves 3 to 6 inches long, hairy beneath, and purple flowers in axillary and terminal panicles. Noted as native to Burma and much larger than Lagerstroemia indica but with less showy flowers.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. A tropical banana relative about 12 feet high with leaves up to 7 feet long and fruits approximately 4 inches long. Reference to previous introduction: see 75282.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. A bulbous perennial 12 to 18 inches high, noted as native to India and tropical America. The flower scape appears before the linear leaves and bears a raceme 6 to 12 inches long of drooping campanulate flowers about an inch long, greenish white with green nerves. Reference to previous introduction: see 103630.

crops.presented_by: Forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun
crops.institution_involved: Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun, United Provinces
crops.description: From India; seeds presented by the forest botanist, Forest Research Institute, Dehra Dun. A bulbous plant known chiefly in cultivation, with linear bright-green leaves about a foot long and bright-yellow, red, or white flowers over an inch long on scapes about 5 inches high. Reference to previous introduction: see 68125.

crops.presented_by: A. N. Steward and H. C. Cheo, University of Nanking
crops.institution_involved: University of Nanking
crops.description: Seeds collected in Kwangsi Province by A. N. Steward and H. C. Cheo of the University of Nanking; received April 28, 1934 and numbered in September 1934. Specimen F. 84 (Li Shu) collected October 23, 1933 at 1,000 feet altitude at Ta Tseh Tsuen, Yung Hsien. Described as a tree with ovate fruits about an inch long and almost as wide.
